1
00:00:49,682 --> 00:00:50,682
<i>Mom!</i>

2
00:00:52,393 --> 00:00:54,227
<i>Mom! Help me.</i>

3
00:00:57,398 --> 00:00:58,398
What is it?

4
00:00:58,482 --> 00:01:01,317
I wasn't dreaming, Walt.
I didn't imagine it.

5
00:01:01,402 --> 00:01:04,571
I heard him. I heard him. I heard him.
I heard Chris.

6
00:01:04,822 --> 00:01:07,448
- I heard him!
- I know.

7
00:01:07,658 --> 00:01:10,159
No. I wasn't imagining it, Walt.

8
00:01:10,578 --> 00:01:13,121
No, I did. He's... He's...

9
00:01:14,331 --> 00:01:16,541
- I heard him!
- Billie.

10
00:03:43,482 --> 00:03:45,525
That's about as far as I can get you.

11
00:03:45,609 --> 00:03:47,235
All right. Thank you.

12
00:04:01,167 --> 00:04:04,502
- You left all your shit on my dash.
- Keep it.

13
00:04:05,504 --> 00:04:07,005
Suit yourself.

14
00:04:07,590 --> 00:04:09,048
Thanks again.

15
00:04:11,010 --> 00:04:12,886
Hey, hold on a minute.

16
00:04:17,141 --> 00:04:20,061
Here, take these.
They'll keep your feet dry.

17
00:04:21,481 --> 00:04:25,358
If you make it out alive, give me a call.
My number's inside the boots.

18
00:04:25,693 --> 00:04:26,860
Thanks.

19
00:09:04,684 --> 00:09:05,851
Hello?

20
00:10:11,501 --> 00:10:15,087
Is there anybody here?

21
00:10:17,966 --> 00:10:19,466
Guess not!

22
00:11:28,079 --> 00:11:30,289
Two years he walks the earth.

23
00:11:37,464 --> 00:11:39,840
No phone, no pool, no pets,

24
00:11:40,967 --> 00:11:42,468
<i>no cigarettes.</i>

25
00:11:59,903 --> 00:12:01,612
Ultimate freedom.

26
00:12:03,531 --> 00:12:07,534
An extremist. An aesthetic voyager

27
00:12:09,329 --> 00:12:13,499
whose home is the road.

28
00:12:14,459 --> 00:12:17,836
"Hey, listen, old man.
Now, don't psychoanalyze me, all right?

29
00:12:18,171 --> 00:12:20,839
"Shut up.
I'm taking you out to where we're going."

30
00:12:20,924 --> 00:12:22,508
"Where you going?"

31
00:12:22,676 --> 00:12:25,344
"I told you. We're going nowhere!"

32
00:12:27,889 --> 00:12:33,519
So now, after two rambling years
comes the final and greatest adventure.

33
00:12:35,105 --> 00:12:38,357
The climactic battle to kill

34
00:12:39,776 --> 00:12:41,694
the false being within

35
00:12:42,862 --> 00:12:46,740
and victoriously conclude
the spiritual revolution.

36
00:13:16,396 --> 00:13:21,066
No longer to be poisoned
by civilization, he flees,

37
00:13:21,901 --> 00:13:24,695
and walks alone
upon the land to become

38
00:13:26,072 --> 00:13:27,698
lost in the wild.

39
00:13:59,232 --> 00:14:04,278
<i>... hard work and manifold contributions
to our community during their time here,</i>

40
00:14:05,238 --> 00:14:08,574
<i>we salute you and offer all of you</i>

41
00:14:08,700 --> 00:14:11,786
<i>one more round of applause
and congratulations.</i>

42
00:14:18,585 --> 00:14:21,379
<i>Nina Lynn Lockwynn.</i>

43
00:14:26,301 --> 00:14:29,512
<i>Vanessa Denise Lowery.</i>

44
00:14:33,892 --> 00:14:37,353
<i>Christopher Johnson McCandless.</i>

45
00:14:48,490 --> 00:14:51,700
<i>Regina Victoria McNabb.</i>

46
00:15:14,850 --> 00:15:18,519
<i>I see them standing at the formal gates
of their colleges.</i>

47
00:15:21,690 --> 00:15:25,734
<i>I see my father strolling out
under the ochre sandstone arch,</i>

48
00:15:26,153 --> 00:15:30,281
<i>the red tiles glinting like bent plates
of blood behind his head.</i>

49
00:15:31,241 --> 00:15:33,993
<i>I see my mother
with a few light books at her hip,</i>

50
00:15:34,077 --> 00:15:37,705
<i>standing at the pillar made of tiny
bricks with the wrought-iron gates</i>

51
00:15:37,789 --> 00:15:41,876
<i>still open behind her,
its sword-tips black in the May air.</i>

52
00:15:42,878 --> 00:15:44,962
<i>They are about to graduate.</i>

53
00:15:46,173 --> 00:15:50,926
<i>They are about to get married.
They are kids. They are dumb.</i>

54
00:15:51,511 --> 00:15:55,556
<i>All they know is they are innocent,
they would never hurt anybody.</i>

55
00:15:57,811 --> 00:16:01,522
<i>I want to go up to them and say,
"Stop, don't do it.</i>

56
00:16:01,773 --> 00:16:05,359
<i>"She's the wrong woman,
he's the wrong man.</i>

57
00:16:05,652 --> 00:16:09,739
<i>"You are going to do things
you cannot imagine you would ever do.</i>

58
00:16:09,907 --> 00:16:12,992
<i>"You are going to do bad things
to children.</i>

59
00:16:13,076 --> 00:16:15,661
<i>"You are going to suffer
in ways you never heard of.</i>

60
00:16:15,746 --> 00:16:17,747
<i>"You are going to want to die."</i>

61
00:16:20,209 --> 00:16:24,253
<i>I want to go up to them there
in the late May sunlight and say it.</i>

62
00:16:24,671 --> 00:16:27,632
<i>But I don't do it. I want to live.</i>

63
00:16:29,635 --> 00:16:33,679
<i>I take them up like the male and female
paper dolls, and bang them together</i>

64
00:16:33,764 --> 00:16:38,768
<i>at the hips like chips of flint, as if
to strike sparks from them. I say,</i>

65
00:16:40,270 --> 00:16:44,815
"Do what you are going to do
and I will tell about it."

66
00:16:46,109 --> 00:16:48,569
Here they are, Walt. Okay?

67
00:16:49,488 --> 00:16:51,197
Who wrote that?

68
00:16:51,698 --> 00:16:56,202
Well, could have been either one of us,
couldn't it?

69
00:16:56,286 --> 00:16:58,996
Why is he letting Carine drive his car?

70
00:16:59,790 --> 00:17:02,416
There's a lot of great poems in here.

71
00:17:07,297 --> 00:17:09,507
I have to speak to her about it.

72
00:17:09,591 --> 00:17:10,633
Sit down.

73
00:17:11,552 --> 00:17:13,386
Excuse me. I'm going to get my son.

74
00:17:13,470 --> 00:17:16,639
He just graduated today
from Emory College.

75
00:17:16,723 --> 00:17:18,015
I'll get it. I'll get it.

76
00:17:18,100 --> 00:17:21,686
Chris, hi!
We've been waiting and waiting.

77
00:17:21,770 --> 00:17:26,148
You scared me half to death
jumping up there on that stage like that.

78
00:17:27,401 --> 00:17:29,652
- Hi, Dad.
- Congratulations, Son.

79
00:17:29,778 --> 00:17:33,155
- This is a big step.
- Thank you, Dad.

80
00:17:33,657 --> 00:17:34,991
All right.

81
00:17:36,243 --> 00:17:38,244
You're not supposed to be driving
in Georgia.

82
00:17:38,328 --> 00:17:39,453
Why? I have my permit.

83
00:17:39,538 --> 00:17:41,747
'Cause it's against the law
for a learner's permit

84
00:17:41,832 --> 00:17:45,251
to drive in another state
from one's home state. That's why.

85
00:17:45,335 --> 00:17:48,754
I didn't know that. I thought that if I was
with a legal driver that it'd be okay.

86
00:17:48,839 --> 00:17:49,839
Well, let's...

87
00:17:59,516 --> 00:18:02,560
- Are they going to continue?
- No.

88
00:18:04,855 --> 00:18:07,523
I guess everybody's celebrating today.

89
00:18:07,733 --> 00:18:11,569
- They're going to stay in the bar, right?
- That's right.

90
00:18:22,958 --> 00:18:26,628
My grades are good enough, I think,
to get into Harvard Law.

91
00:18:26,712 --> 00:18:28,671
Chris, that's wonderful.

92
00:18:30,132 --> 00:18:32,216
That is a big deal.

93
00:18:32,885 --> 00:18:35,595
How much do you have left
in the college fund?

94
00:18:36,055 --> 00:18:41,142
Exactly $24,500.68.

95
00:18:41,226 --> 00:18:42,894
Well, that's specific.

96
00:18:42,978 --> 00:18:45,730
I had to go to the bank
this morning, Mom.

97
00:18:47,399 --> 00:18:51,569
Your mother and I will be glad
to contribute the balance for Harvard.

98
00:18:51,654 --> 00:18:53,112
That's right.

99
00:18:53,405 --> 00:18:54,739
I've got to figure out
what I'm going to do.

100
00:18:54,823 --> 00:18:58,284
I've got a lot of things
to pack and organize here first.

101
00:18:58,369 --> 00:19:02,872
Your father and I,
we want to make a present to you.

102
00:19:03,666 --> 00:19:06,292
We want to get you out of that junker.

103
00:19:06,835 --> 00:19:08,252
What junker?

104
00:19:08,712 --> 00:19:09,962
That.

105
00:19:12,383 --> 00:19:15,718
- We want to buy you a new car.
- That's right.

106
00:19:15,844 --> 00:19:17,261
A new car?

107
00:19:19,515 --> 00:19:21,599
Why would I want a new car?

108
00:19:22,685 --> 00:19:24,394
Datsun runs great.

109
00:19:25,938 --> 00:19:28,731
Do you think I want some fancy boat?

110
00:19:30,567 --> 00:19:33,611
Are you worried
what the neighbors might think?

111
00:19:33,779 --> 00:19:36,572
Well, we weren't gonna get you
a brand new Cadillac, Chris.

112
00:19:36,657 --> 00:19:39,867
We just want to get you a nice new car
that's safe to drive.

113
00:19:39,952 --> 00:19:43,538
And you never know when that thing
out there just might blow up.

114
00:19:43,622 --> 00:19:49,836
Blow up. Blow up?
Are you guys crazy? It's a great car.

115
00:19:50,379 --> 00:19:54,632
I don't need a new car.
I don't want a new car.

116
00:19:54,967 --> 00:19:57,051
- I don't want anything.
- Okay.

117
00:19:57,136 --> 00:20:00,888
- These things, things, things, things.
- Okay.

118
00:20:00,973 --> 00:20:02,765
- Everything has to be difficult.
- Thank you.

119
00:20:02,850 --> 00:20:04,934
- Thank you.
- Maybe that's not what he means.

120
00:20:05,018 --> 00:20:08,688
Maybe he just wants his old car.
It's not such a big deal.

121
00:20:10,983 --> 00:20:13,651
Thank you. I just don't want anything.

122
00:20:23,036 --> 00:20:25,413
<i>Chris measured himself
and those around him</i>

123
00:20:25,497 --> 00:20:28,082
<i>by a fiercely rigorous moral code.</i>

124
00:20:28,167 --> 00:20:29,292
Bye, Chris!

125
00:20:29,626 --> 00:20:32,712
<i>He risked what could have been
a relentlessly lonely path</i>

126
00:20:32,796 --> 00:20:36,509
<i>but found company
in the characters of the books he loved</i>

127
00:20:39,138 --> 00:20:43,349
<i>from writers like Tolstoy,
Jack London and Thoreau.</i>

128
00:20:45,019 --> 00:20:48,188
<i>He could summon their words
to suit any occasion,</i>

129
00:20:48,981 --> 00:20:50,690
<i>and he often would.</i>

130
00:21:06,081 --> 00:21:11,127
<i>I forgot to ask what quote he'd have
picked for his graduation dinner,</i>

131
00:21:11,212 --> 00:21:14,798
<i>but I had a good idea
of who the primary target would be.</i>

132
00:21:19,637 --> 00:21:22,639
<i>It was inevitable
that Chris would break away.</i>

133
00:21:24,683 --> 00:21:28,728
<i>And when he did, he would do it
with characteristic immoderation.</i>

134
00:22:14,775 --> 00:22:19,112
<i>"It should not be denied that being
footloose has always exhilarated us.</i>

135
00:22:20,114 --> 00:22:23,032
<i>"It is associated in our minds
with escape</i>

136
00:22:24,201 --> 00:22:28,037
<i>"from history and oppression and law
and irksome obligations.</i>

137
00:22:29,540 --> 00:22:31,291
<i>"Absolute freedom.</i>

138
00:22:33,544 --> 00:22:35,962
<i>"And the road has always led west."</i>

139
00:24:36,210 --> 00:24:37,711
<i>I need a name.</i>

140
00:25:07,074 --> 00:25:08,950
<i>Toward the end of June,</i>

141
00:25:09,035 --> 00:25:12,078
<i>Emory had mailed our parents
Chris' final grade report.</i>

142
00:25:12,621 --> 00:25:14,247
<i>Almost all A's.</i>

143
00:25:14,665 --> 00:25:17,419
<i>A in Apartheid in South African Society.</i>

144
00:25:18,212 --> 00:25:22,758
<i>A- minus in Contemporary African
Politics and the Food Crisis in Africa.</i>

145
00:25:23,634 --> 00:25:27,012
<i>And on it went. Clever boy, my brother.</i>

146
00:25:28,639 --> 00:25:32,309
<i>But by the end of July,
we hadn't heard anything from him</i>

147
00:25:32,393 --> 00:25:34,936
<i>and my parents
were becoming unsettled.</i>

148
00:25:36,522 --> 00:25:38,899
<i>Chris had never had a phone,</i>

149
00:25:38,983 --> 00:25:42,486
<i>so they decided to drive down
to Atlanta and surprise him.</i>

150
00:25:57,585 --> 00:26:00,337
<i>When they arrived at the apartment,
there was a "For Rent" sign up</i>

151
00:26:00,421 --> 00:26:03,924
<i>and the manager said that Chris
had moved out at the end of May.</i>

152
00:26:04,008 --> 00:26:06,051
Oh, yes. He left two months ago.

153
00:26:06,344 --> 00:26:08,345
<i>So when they got home,</i>

154
00:26:08,429 --> 00:26:12,557
<i>I had to hand them all the letters that
they had sent Chris that summer,</i>

155
00:26:13,142 --> 00:26:16,978
<i>which had been returned in a bundle.</i>

156
00:26:17,355 --> 00:26:21,566
<i>Chris had arranged for the post office
to hold them until August 1st,</i>

157
00:26:21,651 --> 00:26:24,528
<i>to buy himself some time.</i>

158
00:26:25,571 --> 00:26:27,614
Did you know about this?

159
00:26:28,199 --> 00:26:30,117
He didn't say anything.

160
00:26:30,743 --> 00:26:34,287
<i>I understood what he was doing.
That he had spent four years</i>

161
00:26:34,372 --> 00:26:38,458
<i>fulfilling the absurd and tedious duty
of graduating from college,</i>

162
00:26:41,087 --> 00:26:45,549
<i>and now he was emancipated
from that world of abstraction,</i>

163
00:26:45,633 --> 00:26:50,178
<i>false security, parents
and material excess,</i>

164
00:26:51,180 --> 00:26:55,016
<i>the things that cut Chris off
from the truth of his existence.</i>

165
00:28:09,302 --> 00:28:10,469
Hey!

166
00:28:14,474 --> 00:28:17,351
- Hey, man. Step around. Jump in.
- Okay, great.

167
00:28:17,936 --> 00:28:21,188
We barely saw you there
underneath that crazy hat of yours.

168
00:28:21,314 --> 00:28:25,025
This door's a little tricky.
There you go. Hop in.

169
00:28:28,655 --> 00:28:29,863
That's Rainey.

170
00:28:29,948 --> 00:28:31,657
- Hi, Rainey.
- Yeah, I'm Rainey.

171
00:28:31,741 --> 00:28:33,408
- I'm Jan.
- Hi. I'm Alex.

172
00:28:33,493 --> 00:28:34,826
Alex with the hat on.

173
00:28:34,911 --> 00:28:36,995
- Yeah, I know. You said it, man.
- Yeah.

174
00:28:38,748 --> 00:28:40,707
So you're a leather now.

175
00:28:41,960 --> 00:28:43,043
I'm a leather?

176
00:28:43,127 --> 00:28:48,257
Yeah, a leather tramp. That's what they
call the ones that hoof it, go on foot.

177
00:28:49,092 --> 00:28:51,301
Technically we're rubber tramps.

178
00:28:51,386 --> 00:28:53,428
Because we have a vehicle.

179
00:28:54,597 --> 00:28:57,891
- You don't have to push me away.
- Come on, please?

180
00:28:59,394 --> 00:29:04,523
Yeah, Alex could have a vehicle as well,
but he decided to burn all of his money.

181
00:29:06,818 --> 00:29:08,777
And why did you do that?

182
00:29:10,530 --> 00:29:13,865
I don't need money.
Makes people cautious.

183
00:29:16,202 --> 00:29:18,787
Come on, Alex.
You gotta be a little cautious.

184
00:29:18,871 --> 00:29:21,957
I mean, that book of yours is cool
and everything,

185
00:29:22,208 --> 00:29:25,335
but you can't depend entirely
on leaves and berries.

186
00:29:26,462 --> 00:29:30,090
I don't know if you want to depend on
much more than that.

187
00:29:30,967 --> 00:29:33,051
Where are your mom and dad?

188
00:29:36,055 --> 00:29:38,265
Living their lies somewhere.

189
00:29:41,269 --> 00:29:43,812
You look like a loved kid. Be fair.

190
00:29:44,981 --> 00:29:46,064
Fair?

191
00:29:47,066 --> 00:29:48,900
You know what I mean.

192
00:29:51,946 --> 00:29:54,197
I'll paraphrase Thoreau here.

193
00:29:55,201 --> 00:29:59,496
"Rather than love, than money,
than faith,

194
00:29:59,581 --> 00:30:03,625
"than fame, than fairness,

195
00:30:06,046 --> 00:30:07,629
"give me truth."

196
00:30:29,069 --> 00:30:32,112
<i>From as long ago
as Chris and I could remember,</i>

197
00:30:32,280 --> 00:30:35,449
<i>there have been
daily bouts of rage in our house.</i>

198
00:30:35,533 --> 00:30:40,037
<i>Violence that we were forced
to witness. It was very real.</i>

199
00:30:41,956 --> 00:30:44,541
<i>But it was also like theater.</i>

200
00:30:46,044 --> 00:30:50,005
<i>They cast us as both judges
and the accused.</i>

201
00:30:50,340 --> 00:30:55,969
And I got you this token,
this expensive token.

202
00:30:56,388 --> 00:30:58,555
<i>Dad had been the young genius</i>

203
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:03,435
<i>that NASA enlisted to do crucial designs
for the American satellite radar systems</i>

204
00:31:03,520 --> 00:31:08,065
<i>that would be our answer
to the Russian Sputnik.</i>

205
00:31:08,149 --> 00:31:10,567
<i>And Mom and he later started up
a consulting firm</i>

206
00:31:10,652 --> 00:31:14,113
<i>combining her
get-up-and-go resourcefulness</i>

207
00:31:14,197 --> 00:31:15,823
<i>with his wealth of knowledge.</i>

208
00:31:15,907 --> 00:31:18,117
Look at this.

209
00:31:21,162 --> 00:31:24,873
<i>But by the time the company
actually made its first million,</i>

210
00:31:25,208 --> 00:31:30,003
<i>the careerism and money seemed
only to embolden their blindness.</i>

211
00:31:30,630 --> 00:31:32,631
Thank you very, very much.

212
00:31:33,675 --> 00:31:36,218
<i>I remember the first family meeting</i>

213
00:31:36,553 --> 00:31:40,013
<i>to let us in on their plans
for getting a divorce.</i>

214
00:31:40,765 --> 00:31:44,184
<i>They wanted us to choose
which of them we'd live with.</i>

215
00:31:46,187 --> 00:31:48,021
<i>We cried our eyes out.</i>

216
00:31:50,275 --> 00:31:52,484
<i>The divorce never happened,</i>

217
00:31:53,194 --> 00:31:56,363
<i>but the battles and the meetings
never stopped.</i>

218
00:31:57,615 --> 00:32:00,701
<i>It wasn't very long
before Chris and I shut off.</i>

219
00:32:02,579 --> 00:32:05,372
<i>We'd say "Go ahead.</i>

220
00:32:06,958 --> 00:32:08,625
<i>"Get the divorce."</i>

221
00:32:10,044 --> 00:32:14,967
Jeez. If I struck a match to you I'd have
dinner and warmth at the same time.

222
00:32:16,052 --> 00:32:17,720
Where's Jan going?

223
00:32:20,223 --> 00:32:21,849
Well, my friend,

224
00:32:23,393 --> 00:32:25,895
all is not well on the hippie front.

225
00:32:35,572 --> 00:32:38,741
You're an industrious little fucker,
aren't you?

226
00:32:39,951 --> 00:32:41,327
Little bit.

227
00:32:46,291 --> 00:32:50,711
It's funny how things happen
at particular times.

228
00:32:52,672 --> 00:32:56,133
I've loved that woman
for a lot of years, bro.

229
00:32:59,095 --> 00:33:01,764
But, you know, she's got a story.

